quran[11]{c,v,t,f}:
  17,28,"But if you<sup>sg </sup>disregard them, seeking mercy{1}which you expect from your Lord, then speak to them using gentle words.",1:[According to exegetes, ‘mercy’ here means ‘provision’.]
  17,29,"And do not keep your hand tied to your neck{1}nor spread it out fully, lest you end up blamed, regretful.",1:[A metaphor for miserliness.]
  17,30,"Indeed, your Lord extends provision for whomever He wills and He restrains<i>(it) </i>; indeed, He has always been All-Aware, All-Seeing of His servants."
  17,31,"And do<sup>pl </sup>not kill your children for fear of poverty; We provide for them and for you<sup>pl </sup>. Indeed, killing them has always been a grave offense."
  17,32,"And do<sup>pl </sup>not come near fornication; indeed, it is an obscenity and an evil way."
  17,33,"And do<sup>pl </sup>not kill the self which Allah has made inviolable, except in the course of justice. And if someone is killed unjustly, We have given authority to his kinsman who seeks retribution, but he{1}should not be excessivein killing; indeed, he is bound to be aided.",1:[Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…but you<sup>sg</sup> should not be excessive …” should not be excessive …”]
  17,34,"And do<sup>pl </sup>not come near the orphan’s wealth except with that which is better<i>(for him) </i>, until he has attained his full strength. And fulfill every covenant; indeed, the covenant has always been a responsibility."
  17,35,"And give<sup>pl </sup>full measure when you measure, and weigh with accurate scales; that is fair and the best determination."
  17,36,"And do<sup>sg </sup>not follow what you have no knowledge of; indeed, the hearing and the sight and the burning heart—all of those—<i>(one) </i>is bound to be questioned about."
  17,37,"And do<sup>sg </sup>not walk merrily on earth; you<sup>sg </sup>will surely not pierce the earth, nor will you match the mountains in height."
  17,38,"All of that—its evil has always been{1}disliked by your Lord.",1:[Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “All of that has always been an evil deed before your<sup>sg</sup> Lord (and) disliked.” Lord (and) disliked.”]
